Supervised Training Set

$$ D= \{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^N $$ Alternate notation Here $D$ is called the training set and $N$ is the number of training examples.

Unsupervised Training Set

$$ D = \{x_i\}_{i=1}^N $$

Classification

$$ y\in\{1,\dots,C\} $$ With $C$ being the number of classes. $$ p(y|x, D) $$$$ \text{Binary Classification} \quad 1=p(y=1|x,D) + p(y=0|x,D) $$ $$ \text{General Classification} \quad 1=\sum_{c=1}^{C}p(y=c|x,D) $$ $$ \text{Best Guess} \quad \hat{y}=\hat{f}(x)=argmax_{c=1}^{C}\space p(y=c|x,D) $$ Here the $\hat{}$ symbol is being used to denote an estimate from a model.

Regression

Same as classification, except: $$ y_{i}\in\mathbb{R} $$

Approaches

Linear Models & Least Squares

$$ \hat{Y}=\hat{\beta_{0}}+\sum_{j=1}^{p}X_j\hat{\beta_j} $$ or $$ p(y|\mathbf{x},\theta) = \mathcal{N}(y|\mathbf{w}^T\mathbf{x},\sigma^2) $$

can be made to model non-linear relationships by replacing $\mathbf{x}$ with $\phi(\mathbf{x})$ $$ p(y|\mathbf{x},\theta) = \mathcal{N}(y|\mathbf{w}^{T}\phi(\mathbf{x}),\sigma^2) $$

Least Squares

$$ \hat{\theta}\overset{\Delta}{=}\text{arg }\underset{\theta}{\text{max }}\text{log } p(\mathcal{D}|\theta) $$
